observations.recommendation:
We recommended to the Management to establish an internal control system in the repairs and maintenance of its government owned vehicles/properties including the disposal of waste materials/used spare parts thereof.

We further recommended to the management to create a committee to do the pre-repair inspection of all government properties subject for repair and maintenance and another committee to do the post-repair inspection. 

Thereafter, the following must be strictly followed:
a)	Complete supporting documents for repairs of motor vehicles, particularly the requirement of pre-repair evaluation reports, approved detailed plans, post-inspection reports, and the history of repairs;
b)	Ensure that every disposal of waste materials related to vehicle repairs is properly authorized by requiring the certification of correctness of the property officer and the approval of the approving authority, as provided in the NGAS Manual for LGUs;
c)	Ensure the inclusion of vehicle details, particularly the plate number, in the supporting documents to ascertain the validity of the disbursements; 
d)	Ensure the required documents are complete before any payment can be made. 

Also, in order to complete the post audit of the transactions enumerated in Annex G of this report, please submit the following:
1. Justification for the other supporting documents that were not originals or signed, or submit the originals and properly signed copies of the documents; and
2. The lacking required supporting documents marked with “X”.

We recommended to the Management to:
a)	Direct concerned personnel to submit the POs which were not attached in the Disbursement Vouchers, and those that were not signed by the supplier, to complete the post audit of the disbursements (see Annex L of AAR 2022);
b)	Inform respective personnel of the proper filling out of the purchase orders, specifically providing for the delivery dates and date of supplier’s receipt of PO;
c)	Consider other suppliers in the procurement process who can provide better services, such as timely delivery of goods and good quality of materials; and
d)	Assess the LGU’s procurement planning and processes, from preparation of purchase requests, requests for quotation, purchase orders, up to acceptance and inspection of the delivered goods, and to identify specific areas which may need improvement or replacement.

We recommended again to the Management to require the following offices:  
a)     Municipal General Services Office to: 
1.  Maintain an updated stock card per category of Inventories;
2.  Keep complete records of the Inventories of the LGU;
3.  Submit SSMI to MAO to record the inventories using appropriate expenditure accounts;
4.  Undertake the annual physical inventory and reconcile with the records of Municipal Accountant’s Office. 

b)     Municipal Accountant’s Office to: 
1.  Use Perpetual Inventory Method for the recording of inventories and the reconciliation of stock cards and ledger cards;
2.  Maintain an updated Inventory Ledger Cards for each category of inventory assets, and coordinate with GSO with the reconciliation for accounts.

We recommended again to the Management to: 
a) Exert more efforts to retrieve the necessary records to properly identify the specific transactions with unidentified notations by tracing prior year transactions in the Financial Statements in its accounting system; 
b) Set confirmations and inquiries of prior staff holding the same position with regard to those unidentified amounts; 
c) Revisit COA Circular 2016-005 for receivables which remained outstanding for 10 years or more and file for request for write off supported by necessary documentation for submission; and d) Lastly, once identified or taken with action, incorporate in its Notes to Financial Statements in the LGU by making a narrative presentation of the progress of those receivables and determine if settlement/collectability can still be ascertained.

